### EARS — Progress (2026-04-29 08:42)
<!-- concepts: ARM-protocol, agent-discoverability, anti-fraud -->

**Done** (Tasks 7-9 — agent self-discovery layer):
- `GET /api/protocol` (server/routes/bundles.py + arm_service.protocol_descriptor): self-describing endpoint returning required modalities, metric formulas, SSIM cap (0.3), trace anti-fraud checks (6 items), status machine, scorecard formulas, schema URLs, handoff field split (user vs server-computed). Values derived from live constants — no drift.
- `GET /api/schemas/{characterization,trace-step}/v1` added alongside existing arm-manifest schema.
- `/llms.txt` at site root (3.8 KB) + updated `/robots.txt` pointer following the llms.txt convention. Flask routes `serve_llms_txt` / `serve_robots_txt` in app.py serve them as text/plain.
- `derive_violations(validation)` in arm_service.py converts validation report into structured `[{rule, message, fix, docs}]` array. Bundle upload response now always includes `violations[]` + `protocol_url: '/api/protocol'`. Hard-failed uploads return 400; incomplete returns 200 (uploaded but not ready) with violations the agent can act on.
- Tested rules emitted: `required_modality_missing`, `ssim_only_metric`, `expected_outputs_unresolved`, `trace_anti_fraud`, `completeness_below_threshold`.

**Why this matters**: agents now have three independent paths to learn the protocol — passive (llms.txt → protocol), active (introspect /api/protocol on first run), reactive (read violations from a failed upload). All paths route to the same machine-readable contract; an agent that ignores the first two will still learn from a single rejected submission.
